      "source": "Great example üëç\nThis code is **specifically designed** to teach the **difference between arrays and lists**, and it highlights a **very common Java trap** with `Arrays.asList()`.\n\nI‚Äôll explain it **step by step**, then summarize the **rules you should remember forever**.\n\n---\n\n## 1Ô∏è‚É£ Creating an array\n\n```java\nString[] originalArray = new String[] {\"First\", \"Second\", \"Third\"};\n```\n\n* This is a **normal Java array**\n* Fixed size = 3\n* Index-based\n* Mutable elements (you can change values)\n\nMemory:\n\n```\noriginalArray ‚Üí [\"First\", \"Second\", \"Third\"]\n```\n\n---\n\n## 2Ô∏è‚É£ Converting array ‚Üí list using `Arrays.asList`\n\n```java\nvar originalList = Arrays.asList(originalArray);\n```\n\n### ‚ö†Ô∏è This is the MOST IMPORTANT LINE in this program\n\nWhat **actually happens**:\n\n* `originalList` is a **fixed-size List**\n* It is **backed by the array**\n* NO new collection is created\n\nThink of it like:\n\n```\noriginalArray ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îê\n                ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ SAME DATA\noriginalList ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îÄ‚îò\n```\n\nThey share the **same storage**.\n\n---\n\n## 3Ô∏è‚É£ Modifying the list modifies the array\n\n```java\noriginalList.set(0, \"one\");\n```\n\n* `set()` is allowed\n* You are changing element at index `0`\n\nNow print:\n\n```java\nSystem.out.println(\"list: \" + originalList);\nSystem.out.println(\"array: \" + Arrays.toString(originalArray));\n```\n\n### Output:\n\n```\nlist: [one, Second, Third]\narray: [one, Second, Third]\n```\n\n‚û° Changing the list **changed the array**.\n\n---\n\n## 4Ô∏è‚É£ Sorting the list also sorts the array\n\n```java\noriginalList.sort(Comparator.naturalOrder());\n```\n\nBecause:\n\n* List is backed by the array\n* Sorting the list rearranges the array elements\n\nPrinting again:\n\n```java\nSystem.out.println(\"array: \" + Arrays.toString(originalArray));\n```\n\n### Output:\n\n```\narray: [Second, Third, one]\n```\n\n---\n\n## 5Ô∏è‚É£ Why `add()` is commented out\n\n```java\n// originalList.add(\"fourth\");\n```\n\nIf you uncomment this, you get:\n\n```\nUnsupportedOperationException\n```\n\n### Why?\n\n* `Arrays.asList()` returns a **fixed-size list**\n* You cannot change its size\n* `add()` and `remove()` are not allowed\n\n---\n\n## 6Ô∏è‚É£ Creating a list without an array\n\n```java\nList<String> newList = Arrays.asList(\"Sunday\", \"Monday\", \"Tuesday\");\n```\n\nThis creates:\n\n* A **fixed-size list**\n* Backed by an **internal array**\n* Same rules apply\n\nPrinting:\n\n```\n[Sunday, Monday, Tuesday]\n```\n\n‚ùå Still cannot `add()` or `remove()`\n\n---\n\n# üß† CORE RULES (VERY IMPORTANT)\n\n## Rule 1Ô∏è‚É£ `Arrays.asList(array)`\n\n* Fixed-size list\n* Backed by the array\n* Changes reflect both ways\n\n## Rule 2Ô∏è‚É£ What you CAN do\n\n```java\nset()\nget()\nsort()\n```\n\n## Rule 3Ô∏è‚É£ What you CANNOT do\n\n```java\nadd()\nremove()\nclear()\n```\n\n---\n\n## ‚ö†Ô∏è Common interview trap\n\n```java\nList<String> list = Arrays.asList(array);\nlist.add(\"x\"); // ‚ùå Runtime exception\n```\n\n---\n\n## ‚úÖ How to do it correctly (MOST OF THE TIME)\n\nIf you want a **normal, resizable list**, do this:\n\n```java\nList<String> list = new ArrayList<>(Arrays.asList(originalArray));\n```\n\nNow:\n\n```java\nlist.add(\"fourth\"); // ‚úÖ\n```\n\n---\n\n## üîÅ Comparison table (memorize this)\n\n| Method                 | Size    | Backed by array | Modifiable   |\n| ---------------------- | ------- | --------------- | ------------ |\n| `new String[]`         | Fixed   | ‚Äî               | Values only  |\n| `Arrays.asList()`      | Fixed   | ‚úÖ               | `set()` only |\n| `List.of()`            | Fixed   | ‚ùå               | ‚ùå            |\n| `new ArrayList<>(...)` | Dynamic | ‚ùå               | ‚úÖ            |\n\n---\n\n## üéØ Final takeaway\n\n> `Arrays.asList()` does **not** give you a normal `ArrayList`.\n> It gives you a **view of the array** with list behavior.\n\nThis example is **classic Java interview material**, so you‚Äôre learning exactly the right thing üëç\n\nIf you want next, I can:\n\n* Show this bug in real production code\n* Explain why Java designed it this way\n* Compare with `List.of()`\n* Show how to safely convert between array ‚Üî list\n\nJust tell me üôÇ\n",
